data.content:
## What breaks

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already didn't support sync operations natively but let you opt in to **sync-over-async** (blocking on the async call). In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there is no workaround flag anymore.

## What to do

Convert all data-access methods to their `async` counterparts:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
| Sync (broken in .NET 11) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

The async LINQ extensions live in `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` — you likely already have the `using` directive.

This is an async-all-the-way change, so every **caller** up the chain must also become async. Start from the repository and propagate `async`/`await` up through services and controllers.
